posts.name: Alastair
posts.cooked:
Just use single-flute tools for everything. You can get away with 2-3 flute tools if your using large 1/4" tools, but you will have to slow down your spindle and then you won’t have the torque to cut fast.

My current feed rates are:

For the 4mm Single Flute Ozzy Endmills (this should be similar for the WCPs, though they may be a different quality):
- Keep spindle speed at maximum RPM for small tools.
- Slotting with mist coolant: 1.6mm/0.060" DOC, 80-100IPM.
- Pocketing/Clearing: Full DOC in 1/4" or 3/8", 1.6mm/0.060" stepover at 80-100IPM.

For the 6mm Single Flute Ozzy Endmill:
- Use speeds around 20-24K RPM and 100-120IPM.
- Tool depth: 1/8" DOC. Usually adjust feed and speeds in Mach3.
- Pocketing, full DOC, and 0.1" stepover at 120IPM.

I achieve excellent results with zero welding or burrs when using these speeds combined with plenty of mist coolant.

Here are some helpful videos:
- [Video 1](https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=zNMNG9PG7uk) - Could be plunging much faster
- [Video 2](https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=3E4aNLS1xYc) - Aluminum pocketing with 4mm OzzyEndmill
- [Video 3](https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=e5HQOZXYJR0) - X6 CNC aluminum production

Note: The 4mm Huhao on an X6 machine, which is slightly more rigid than an X8.

posts.name: Nick Aarestad
posts.cooked: We've mostly been running one part at a time—I’ve seen a few strategies for doing multiple/nested parts in F360, but nothing seems particularly great—what are people doing about this?
I end up making an assembly file in SW instead and import that.

posts.name: Parth Oza
posts.cooked: I've been doing something—not the most efficient method, but I carry it out in Fusion after importing STEP files. Essentially, I join all unique components so they lie in the same plane. After eliminating the joints, I rearrange the pieces to ensure they fit better between each other without excessive waste. When needing to create multiple identical parts, like last year’s elevator gussets, I arrange them in a tileable pattern and reuse copies. If fitting them into the leftover stock proves challenging, I measure the maximum distance between the parts and ensure they’ll fit together. If you still don’t understand, feel free to ask for clarification. Despite spending considerable time on it, efficiency-wise, it wasn’t terrible, though it was quite labor-intensive.

posts.name: page2067
posts.cooked:
Thanks for the post.

We require the name and source of the 750 W silent compressor. Currently, our setup uses only a vacuum, similar to your experience.

posts.name: Alastair
posts.cooked: Having bought and used several 750w compressors from different brands within China and Australia I can tell you this. They are pretty much all the same all the ones on the market in Australia or the US no matter how they are branded are all just white label Chinese compressors. Something to think about is some of the smaller silent compressors don’t have a regulator which can cause problems if your wanting to use them for pneumatic tools but makes no difference for a mist cooling system. Mine is just a generic cheap ebay model which was about $100 works fine and is really quiet in comparison with the large direct drive compressor I was using previously. As long as it has the all in one round compressor + motor thing and has good rubber shock mounts between the motor and the tank body it will be nice and quiet no matter the brand. Something like this is what you want: California Air Tools 4710SQ Quiet Flow 1.0 Hp 4.7 Gal. Steel Tank Air Compressor Free 2-day shipping. Buy California Air Tools 4710SQ Quiet Flow 1.0 Hp 4.7 Gal. Steel Tank Air Compressor at Walmart.com. Would definitely recommend a small silent oil-less compressor from any brand for running a mist coolant system or for running pneumatic tools in your shop.

posts.name: Phil McJoe
posts.cooked: What characteristics make the Omoio cut exponentially better than other routers at that price point?

posts.name: Brian Wagg
posts.cooked: The product page for the OMIO X8-2200L (available on https://www.omiocnc.com/products/x8-2200l-usb.html) provides some helpful visuals. The OMIO X8-2200L boasts an extremely robust construction utilizing heavy plate aluminum to enhance rigidity. Compared to other similarly priced routers, its build feels significantly stronger. When making precise cuts in challenging materials like aluminum, it’s crucial that the router frame remains stable; the OMIO avoids this issue through its design. Additionally, the machine employs HG20 linear guide rails instead of conventional hardened steel components, further improving accuracy and rigidity. The drive system features ball screws to minimize backlash and boost repeatability. The spindle is equipped with a 2200W water-cooled motor, keeping it cool during heavy workloads. Overall, the OMIO stands out as a durable option within its price range, combining high-quality components to deliver excellent performance.

posts.name: Ari Meles-Braverman
posts.cooked: You could wire a few more in series. I'm no expert, but shouldn't the switches be wired in parallel? If they're wired in series they all need to be pressed for the signal to get through. If they're in parallel then any of them being pressed will let the signal through.
